					<h2 class="r-fit-text">SARDINE</h2>
					<h2 class="r-fit-text">A Modular Python Live Coding Environment</h2>
					<p><b>Raphaël Maurice Forment (ECLLA, UJM)</p></b>
					<p><b>Jack Armitage (IIL Labs)</b></p>
				</section>

				<section>
				<h4 style="font-size: 24pt; letter-spacing: 0.05em">BIOGRAPHY</h4>
				<section>
					<ul>
					<li style="font-size: 22pt;"> <b>Raphaël Maurice Forment: </b> PhD Student at the ECLLA laboratory (Université Jean Monnet de Saint-Étienne). I am doing a transdisciplinary research 
					(musicology, computer science, social sciences) about live coding tools, their usage and how the tools are transformed by the discourses and practices that accompany the different practices 
					and views on live coding.
					</ul>
				</section>

				<section>
					<ul>
					<li style="font-size: 22pt;"> <b>Jack Armitage: </b> Postdoctoral research fellow at the Intelligent Instruments Lab. 
					Doctorate in Media and Arts Technologies from Queen Mary University of London, where he studied in Prof. Andrew McPherson's 
					Augmented Instruments Lab. BSc in Music, Multimedia & Electronics from the University of Leeds. His research interests include embodied 
					interaction, craft practice and design cognition. He also produces, performs and live codes music as Lil Data, as part of the PC Music 
					record label.
					</ul>
				</section>

				<section>
					<ul>
					<li style="font-size: 22pt;"> <b>Open-source contributors: </b> 
					<em>thegamecracks (John Phan)</em> (clock, design, architecture), <em>HighHarmonics2</em> (documentation and bug chasing),
					<em>Ralt144MI (Rémi Georges)</em> (crash testing and bugfixing), <em>Miika Alonen</em> (Ziffers integration), <em>TWal</em>
					(parser refactoring), mugulmd, JMPothelune, jarmitage, jure2018, hatchjaw, lutangar, giohappy, and <b>many others :)</b>
					</ul>
				</section>
				</section>

				<section>
				<h4 style="font-size: 24pt; letter-spacing: 0.05em">RATIONALE</h4>

				<section>
				<p style="font-size: 22pt">Sardine development initially started as a tool for analysing and documenting live coding practices:</p>
				<ul style="font-size: 20pt">
			 		<li> Studying/documenting live coding principles and idioms
			 		<li> Developing a playground for live coding notations
			 		<li> Customization, Extendability, Modularity
				</ul>
				</section>
			 
				<section>
					<h2>Live coding idioms</h2>
					<ul style="font-size: 20pt">
						<li> Centered on <em>temporal recursive functions</em> idioms, a central design pattern in the history of musical live coding.
						<li> <em>Imperative</em>, <em>declarative</em> and <em>~functional~</em> approaches to musical patterning.
						<li> Support for <em>modern</em> features: collaborative jamming, Ableton Link Clock support.
					</ul>
				</section>


				<section>
					<h2 class="r-fit-text">Playground for live coding notations</h2>
					<ul style="font-size: 25pt"> 
						<li> <em>Sardine Pattern Language</em>: a basic parser for patterns.
						<li> <em>Ziffers Numeric Language</em>: a parser for chords / melodies.
						<li> <em>Python for hackability</em>: custom pattern language design.
					</ul>
				</section>

				<section>
					<h2 class="r-fit-text">Customization / Extendability</h2>
					<ul style="font-size: 25pt"> 
						<li> Full support for <b>MIDI</b> and <b>OSC</b> protocols (in and out): reactive code, 
						     polling controller values, 
  		  		<li> Definition of custom <b>MIDI</b> instruments and controllers.
						<li> <b>Integrating foreign libraries</b>: Sardine is just regular Python code.
					</ul>
				</section>

				</section>


				<section>
				<h2>Documentation</h2>
